fields.description:
It would be great to see the full list of available parameters for [Customising Email Notifications|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/SgECCQ].

For example, include the review due date parameter to the state changed template:
{noformat}
${notification.review.dueDate?datetime}
{noformat}

Extracted from CRUC-2471:

{quote}
Polish (and probably also other non-English) characters are incorrectly passed to JIRA. That is they are displayed correctly in Crucible, but JIRA issue contains rubbish characters instead of Polish ones. Encoding problems?
{quote}

Refer to [FSH-2638|https://support.atlassian.com/browse/FSH-2638]:
{quote}
When I was using 1.6.6, and I set this property (enable-line-history) to false, the graph disappeared. BUT currently with 2.0.4 despite the fact that it's false, I still can see it. Maybe I missed something, but I can't see the difference of having it true or false.
{quote}

Steps to reproduce:
# Go to {{Administration > Repository List > View (next to REPO) > Properties}}, set the "enable-line-history" to false (see [properties.png|^properties.png])
# Go to {{Administration > Repository List > View (next to REPO) > Indexer > Maintenance > Re-index Linecount Data}}
# Go to 'Source' tab and click on the 'Activity' tab, see the history graph still exists. (see [line-history.png|^line-history.png])

The problem is reproducible in 2.0.6 but not in 1.6.6

Add a comment to the review with this sentences:

{noformat}
There's no doubt the designers knew about the more advanced uses of Spring AOP, using Introductions here.  The question is do we need this level of complexity that a custom framework provides?  Do we want to spend the resources needed to become familiar with a custom framework?  Would using straight Hibernate be sufficient?
{noformat}

Some of the first characters will be missing when exporting it as Text (Tools -> Download Review as Text)

However, when adding the comment as below, the review in text can be displayed properly:

{noformat}
There's no doubt the designers knew about the more advanced uses of Spring AOP, using Introductions here. The question is do we need this level of complexity that a custom framework provides?  Do we want to spend the resources needed to become familiar with a custom framework?  Would using straight Hibernate be sufficient?
{noformat}

Those comments can be displayed properly in the UI but not as the text. Please see these screenshots for a clearer picture: [from the UI|^UI.JPG], [Download review as text|^text.JPG]

I just got bitten for the first time by the fact that Crucible now supports Confluence-style emoticons in comments.  These hated things have been annoying Confluence users for years.  You already have an issue suggesting improving their performance [CRUC-2102]. In terms of value vs annoyance I'm not sure that they are worthwhile in Confluence and really don't want them in Crucible.

I urge you to do this before releasing 2.1, since it's much much easier to never put them in than it is to take them out.

For anybody coming across this request wondering how to avoid an emoticon, just put a backslash in front of its start.  Eg
{noformat}
\(on)
{noformat}

When JSON produces lists of objects, the structures produced depend on the number of items in the list. 
If the {{/reviews-v1/filter}} URL above returns a single review, the JSON will look like this: 
{code} 
{"reviews": 
{"reviewData": {...attributes of review...}} 
} 
{code} 
but if several reviews are returned the JSON will be: 
{code} 
{"reviews": 
{"reviewData": [{...first review...},{...second review},...]} 
} 
{code} 
and if there are no reviews it will simply be: 
{code} 
{"reviews": ""} 
{code} 

Handling this inconsistency in REST clients requires extra code and extra testing.
